# 4. Preparatory Functions (G Codes)

Preparatory functions define how the machine interprets motion, coordinates, and machining logic.

---

# 4.1 Modal vs Non-Modal Functions

## Modal Functions

Modal functions remain active until replaced by another function in the same group.

Example:
If G90 (absolute mode) is programmed, it remains active until G91 is called.

## Non-Modal Functions

Non-modal functions are valid only in the block where they are written.

Example:
G53 applies only to the specific movement block.

Understanding this distinction prevents unexpected machine behavior.

---

# 4.2 Plane Selection

Plane selection defines which axes are active for circular interpolation and cutter compensation.

| Code | Plane                         |
| ---- | ----------------------------- |
| G17  | XY Plane (default at startup) |
| G18  | XZ Plane                      |
| G19  | YZ Plane                      |

---

# 4.3 Unit System Selection

| Code | Description               |
| ---- | ------------------------- |
| G70  | Inch units (Modal).       |
| G71  | Millimeter units (Modal). |

---

# 4.4 Coordinate Programming Modes

## G90 – Absolute Programming

Coordinates are referenced from the active work zero (G54–G57).

## G91 – Incremental Programming

Coordinates are referenced from the current tool position.

---

# 4.5 Motion Behavior Modes

| Code | Description                                               |
| ---- | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| G64  | Continuous mode. Machine blends movements between blocks. |
| G60  | Exact stop mode. Machine stops at the end of each block.  |
| G94  | Feed rate defined in units per minute.                    |

Note:
G60 is cancelled when G64 is activated.

---

# 4.6 Work Coordinate Systems

| Code Range | Description                                           |
| ---------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| G54 – G57  | Programmable work offsets (multiple zero references). |

These allow machining multiple setups without rewriting the program.

---

# 4.7 Machine Coordinate System

| Code | Description                                        |
| ---- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| G53  | Movement in machine coordinate system (Non-Modal). |

Used to bypass work offsets and move relative to the machine’s fixed origin.

